Weather: the breeze was coming off the lake and blowing in a frigid manner. This was Ray Schalk Day at Wrigley Field, several hundred fans from the south side gathering to pay homage to the Giant coach and former White Sox great.  Just before the game his admirers presented him with a set of golf clubs and a travelling bag while members of both teams gathered at the plate.  Mgr McGraw then announced that Schalk would catch this game, Schalk's first NL appearance.
Weather: comfortable, the wind came from Kansas instead of Mackinac Island.  The home run winds come from Kansas.

Hit in the face and fell beside the plate.  The players surrounded him and he finally arose and was escorted to the bench where the bleeding soon ceased upon application of cold water. $A thunderstorm was blowing up out of the West and it became so dark that at times the outfielders were almost obscured, while the wind blew the dust in swirling clouds over the infield. Spectators in the front rows of the stands retreated.

$The rain began to fall and the thunder rolled and lightning flashed.  The downpour became so heavy that Umpire Pfirman called time, the teams withdrawing from the field.  By this time the storm approached proportions of a cloudburst. After a delay of 30 minutes, the umpires inspected the muddy field and decided that with some attention from the ground- keepers the ground could be put in shape for resuming the game.  New bases were placed on it and the groundkeepers set to work to put the field in shape.  Under the direction of the umpires sand was spread on the base lines.  The dugouts were knee-deep in water and were being drained. Total delay: 75 minutes.
$Special ground rules in force due to fans on outfield grass

Ladies' Day; a half-hour before game time all seats were filled.  The overflow crowd was allowed on the field; a hit into any part of the overflow crowd went as a two-bagger.

Over Cuyler's head, the ball dropping into the crowd, but it was difficult for the umpires to see if the ball had cleared the screen in front of the right field bleachers.  Hendrick was stopped at 3B by Ump Moran.  Immediately the Dodgers rushed off their bench claiming that the hit cleared the screen for a home run.  There was a long argument, but the Dodgers' kick was in vain.
'Cuyler sent the crowd into an uproar when he singled past Moore, scoring Wilson with the tying run.  Wilson beat Hendrick's perfect throw to the plate by a narrow margin...'

Baseball-Reference.com writes, 'In the eighth inning of a 5-5 game at Wrigley Field, Cubs 3B Norm McMillan hits a line drive down the LF line with the bases loaded. Reds LF Evar Swanson, shaded toward center, can't find the ball, which he sees bounce off a gutter in foul territory. McMillan circles the bases and four runs score. Later, Cubs relief P Ken Penner picks up his jacket in the bullpen and discovers the ball in his right sleeve.'
